Description. Female: body (
Fig. 144
) length 1–1.3 mm , dorsally with reddish-brownish pigmentation, sometimes unpigmented.

Head (
Fig. 145
): Eyes 1 + 1 , more or less pigmented (with pigmented spots in alcohol and clear on slides). Clypeal area with axial seta in row a. Interantennal area with axial seta in row β. Frontal area with 3 axial setae in rows A, B and C. 8 setae of frontal area are weakly spine-like (in row C: 2 + 2 ; D: 2 + 2 ) (
Fig. 151
).

Antennae 1.9–2.1 times as long as head. Ant I: II: III: IV = 1 : 2.1–2.5 : 3.3–4.2 : 8.3–10.2 . Ant I with 7 setae; Ant II with 15 setae (
Fig. 158
). Ant III (
Fig. 159
): slightly thickened in subbasal – middle part, with 18 setae and 2 sense rods; seta Aai very small and curved; setae Api and Ape shorter and thinner than others. Ant IV (
Fig. 160
) usually distinctly subdivided into 5 (rarely 6 or 7 ) subsegments with 13 ( 12 ) setal whorls. If 5 subsegments present, basal one is 1.6–1.8 times as long as apical one and 1–1.1 times as long as Ant III. Subsegmental formula: 1 + 3 + 1 = (A + M 1 –M 2 ) + (M 3 –M 5 ) + (B).

Foreleg: precoxae and coxa with 1 , 0, 1 setae respectively (
Fig. 146
). Trochanter with 3 anterior and 1 posterior setae; femur with 12–13 setae (
Fig. 163
), seta a 4 turned perpendicularly to the longitudinal axis of the segment. Tibiotarsus (
Fig. 164
) with 3 setae FP and seta FSa; whorl I with 9 setae among which Ja is curved and spiny; each of whorls II–V with 8 setae. Claw without tunica, with inner tooth and 2 pairs of lateral teeth; empodium narrow, with corner tooth, apical filament exceeding claw (
Fig. 164
). Claw 4.0– 4.6 times shorter than tibiotarsus.

Mid leg: precoxae 1, 2 and coxa with 1, 1, 3 setae respectively (
Fig. 146
). Trochanter with anterior trochanteral organ, 3 anterior and 1 posterior setae; femur with 14 setae (
Fig. 166
). Tibiotarsus (
Fig. 165
): 3 setae FP and seta FSa present; whorl I with 9 setae, each of whorls II–IV with 8 setae, whorl V with 7 setae. Claw with tunica, broader than in foreleg, with inner tooth and 2 pairs of lateral teeth; empodium broadened in basal half, with corner tooth and apical filament exceeding claw (
Fig. 165
). Claw 4.5–5 times shorter than tibiotarsus.

Hind leg: precoxae and coxa with 1, 1, 3 setae respectively (
Fig. 146
). Trochanter as in mid leg; femur with 14 setae: 2 posterior ones are very small (
Fig. 167
). Chaetotaxy of tibiotarsus as in mid leg. Claw with tunica, a little broader than mid claw, with inner tooth and 2 pairs of lateral teeth; empodium broader than in mid leg, without tooth, apical filament exceeding claw (
Fig. 168
). Claw 5.5–6.2 times shorter than tibiotarsus.

Ventral tube with 2 small subapical setulae, smooth and long eversible sacks. Tenaculum (
Fig. 157
): rami 3 -dentate, with basal appendage; anterior lobe with 2 apical setulae; tip of posterior lobe exceeding tip of anterior lobe.

Furca (
Fig. 171
): manubrium with 7 + 7 posterior setae. Dens: setae Ie, Ii, IIpe, IIIpi and IVpi are spinelike; outer spine Ie very strong, elongated and looks somewhat articulated (
Fig. 156
); setae Ipe, IIIpe–Vpe simple; 3, 2, 1, 1 setae on anterior side (
Fig. 171
;
Table 3
). Tip of mucro rounded, slightly broadened (
Fig. 162
). Dens 1.5–1.7 times as long as mucro.

Great abdomen (
Fig. 146
): mesothorax with spiny dorsal setae (
Fig. 150
), which are longer than other anterior setae (
Fig. 149
); posterior lateral complex with 6 setae; furca base complex with 9 setae; ventral complex with 3 setae; posterior dorsal complex with setae at least as long as hind claw (
Fig. 148
); the most posterior seta of dI-row (
Fig. 147
) is 1.5 times longer than hind claw and longer than axial seta ms 1 of Abd VI (
Fig. 153
). Trichobothrial complex: AB a little shorter than BC; ABC form an angle about 160 o. Single seta of p-row of Abd I is located below the level of trichobothrium B anteriorly to the trichobothrial complex (marked with arrow); seta b 1 lies close to the line between trichobothria B and C; seta c 1 of thichobothrial complex lies on the level of trichobothrium C or lower.

Fifth abdominal segment with trichobothrium D and 4 setae (
Fig. 146
).

Sixth abdominal segment (
Fig. 169
): circumanal setae strong but not much thickened (
Figs 152, 153
). Appendices anales inserted in papilla, turned towards genital opening and palmated in distal part (
Figs 154–155
); about 1.3 times shorter than hind claw.

P. principalis skelicus


ssp. nov.

is also very close to described above 

P. pseudoprincipalis

but differs from it in following features: 
1
) broadened tip of mucro; 
2
) longer antennae; 
3
) not thickened setae Ipe, IIIpe–Vpe of dens; 
4
) longer dorsal posterior setae of great abdomen and longer setae of a and m rows of Abd VI; 
5
) less palmated appendices anales; 
6
) somewhat greater ratio ‘dens: mucro’.
